rey, England":"Shere, Surrey, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shere, Guildford, Surrey, England":"Shere, Surrey, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Dorking, Mole Valley, Surrey, England":"Dorking, Surrey, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1292–":"1292–Deceased","1292–Female":"1292–Deceased","1275–1320":"1275–1320","1297–1337":"1297–1337","1305–Male":"1305–Deceased","1268–Male":"1268–Deceased","1272–Female":"1272–Deceased","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1268":"1268","1320":"1320","1297":"1297","1275":"1275","1272":"1272","about 1297":"about 1297","1292":"1292","1291":"1291","Shere, Surrey, England":"Shere, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Shere, Guildford, Surrey, England":"Shere, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","Dorking, Mole Valley, Surrey, England":"Dorking, Surrey, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Westcott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Devon and Somerset): habitational name from any of various minor places called with Old English <i>west</i> ‘west’ + <i>cot</i> ‘cottage, shelter’, for example Westcott (Surrey, Devon, Buckinghamshire), Westcot (Berkshire), or Westcote in (Gloucestershire, Hampshire, and Warwickshire)."],"variants":[{"name":"Wescott","meanings":["English (southwestern): variant of   Westcott  ."]},{"name":"Wescoat","meanings":["English: variant of   Westcott  ."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud Westcott was born in 1292, in Dorking, Surrey, England, United Kingdom, her father, William Westcott of La Vallee, Surrey, was 24 and her mother, Mrs. William Westcott, was 20. She married Thomas Weston in 1305, in Shere, Surrey, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in Shere, Surrey, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1292–":"1292–Surnud","1292–Female":"1292–Surnud","1275–1320":"1275–1320","1297–1337":"1297–1337","1305–Male":"1305–Surnud","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1272–Female":"1272–Surnud","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1268":"1268","1320":"1320","1297":"1297","1275":"1275","1272":"1272","about 1297":"umbes 1297","1292":"1292","1291":"1291","Shere, Surrey, England":"Shere, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shere, Guildford, Surrey, England":"Shere, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Dorking, Mole Valley, Surrey, England":"Dorking, Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1292–":"1292–Kuollut","1292–Female":"1292–Kuollut","1275–1320":"1275–1320","1297–1337":"1297–1337","1305–Male":"1305–Kuollut","1268–Male":"1268–Kuollut","1272–Female":"1272–Kuollut","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1268":"1268","1320":"1320","1297":"1297","1275":"1275","1272":"1272","about 1297":"noin 1297","1292":"1292","1291":"1291","Shere, Surrey, England":"Shere, Surrey, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shere, Guildford, Surrey, England":"Shere, Surrey, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta